Creating & setting custom theme


theme_viny_bright <- function(){
  
  library(ggthemes)
  
  ggthemes::theme_fivethirtyeight() %+replace%
  
  theme(
    axis.title = element_text(),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 8),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    strip.background = element_blank(),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
    legend.key = element_rect(fill = NA),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,
                              size = 19,
                              face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
      )
  
  }

theme_set(theme_viny_bright())

also setting months levels correctly so that it can be sorted by calender order of month

data <- data %>% 
    mutate(across(is.character, factor),
           month = str_to_title(month), # this will correct text style to month.abbr
           month = factor(month, levels = month.abb), # this will sort the months
           month = factor(month))  # this will drop two unused levels - Jan, Feb

data %>% 
  select(where(is.factor)) %>% 
  
  imap(function(feature_value, feature_name) {
    
    count(data.frame(x = feature_value), x) %>% 
    mutate(x = fct_reorder(x, n)) %>% 
      
      ggplot(aes(x = x, y = n)) +
      geom_col() +
      coord_flip() +
      labs(title = feature_name)
  })

Outlier treatment

from: E:\3. RPractice\1.DataPreProcessing_HousingPrices.Rmd

# outlier_cap <- function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
#   
#   upper_cap = 3 * quantile(x, 0.99, na.rm = T)
#   lower_cap = 0.3 * quantile(x, 0.01, na.rm = T)
#   
#   x[x > upper_cap] = upper_cap
#   x[x < lower_cap] = lower_cap
#   
#   x <- x
# }

from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13339685/how-to-replace-outliers-with-the-5th-and-95th-percentile-values-in-r


# outlier_cap <- function(x) {
#   quantiles <- quantile(x, c(0.05, 0.95) )
#   
#   x[x < quantiles[1]] <- quantiles[1]
#   x[x > quantiles[2]] <- quantiles[2]
#   
#   x
# }
outlier_cap <- function(x, na.rm = TRUE){
  
  upper_cap = quantile(x, 0.99, na.rm = T)
  lower_cap = quantile(x, 0.01, na.rm = T)
  
  x[x > upper_cap] = upper_cap
  x[x < lower_cap] = lower_cap
  
  x <- x
}
train <- train %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, outlier_cap) 

# confirming if outlier capping worked or not

Note that we have added y as factor otherwise it would have got added as data frame and we would have to use pull(y) for ml formulas.

Since appending Y as factor is causing NA in the oclumn so quiting this step of adding Y as factor

RFE

https://www.machinelearningplus.com/machine-learning/caret-package/

http://topepo.github.io/caret/recursive-feature-elimination.html#rfe

this also took around 32 mins

control <- rfeControl(functions = rfFuncs, method = "cv", verbose = FALSE)

system.time(
  RFE_both_smpl_res <- rfe(x = subset(selected_vars, select = -y),    #  selected_vars[, 1:44]
                 y = pull(selected_vars$y), 
                 sizes = c(7, 15, 20),
                 rfeControl = control
                 )
)

df_test <- cbind(mars1_pred_no_prob, train_both_sample$y) %>%
            rename(prob = mars1_pred_no_prob, Class = y)

df_test <- as.data.frame(df_test)

head(df_test)
plot_pred_type_distribution <- function(df_test, threshold = 0.5) {
  v <- rep(NA, nrow(df_test))
  v <- ifelse(df_test$prob >= threshold & df_test$Class == "no", "TP", v)
  v <- ifelse(df_test$prob >= threshold & df_test$Class == "yes", "FP", v)
  v <- ifelse(df_test$prob < threshold & df_test$Class == "no", "FN", v)
  v <- ifelse(df_test$prob < threshold & df_test$Class == "yes", "TN", v)
  
  df_test$pred_type <- v
  
  ggplot(data=df_test, aes(x=Class, y=prob)) +
    geom_violin(fill= "gray",alpha=0.6, color="NA") +
    geom_jitter(aes(color=pred_type), alpha=0.6) +
    geom_hline(yintercept=threshold, color="red", alpha=0.6) +
    scale_color_discrete(name = "type") +
    labs(title=sprintf("Results Tradeoff at Threshold %.2f", threshold)) +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 20))
}
plot_pred_type_distribution(df_test, threshold = 0.5) 

plot_pred_type_distribution(df_test, threshold = 0.71)

threshold_confmatrix <- function(threshold_major_class = 0.5){
  confusionMatrix(table(predict(model_mars_5_both_smpl, type="prob")[,"yes"] >= (1- threshold_major_class),
                      train_both_sample$y == "yes"))
}

threshold_fn <- function(model_name = model_mars_5_both_smpl, cutoff__prob_yes = 0.3) {
  
  model_prediction <- predict({{model_name}}, newdata = test, type = "prob")["yes"]
  # cutoff__prob_yes = 0.3
  
  model_prediction[model_prediction > cutoff__prob_yes] = "yes"
  model_prediction[model_prediction < cutoff__prob_yes] = "no"
  
  # model_prediction %>%  head()
  
  confusionMatrix(reference = pull(Y_test), as.factor(pull(model_prediction)), positive = "yes")
}

Ratings on test data

library(gt)
library(htmltools)
library(fontawesome)

stars function

rating_stars5 <- function(rating, max_rating = 5){
  rounded_rating <- floor(rating + 0.5)
  stars <- lapply(seq_len(max_rating), function(i){
    if(i <= rounded_rating){
      fontawesome::fa("star", fill = "orange")
    } else{
      fontawesome::fa("star", fill = "grey")
    }
  })
  label <- sprintf("%s out of %s", rating, max_rating)
  # label <- glue("{rating} out of {max_rating}")
  div_out <- div(title = label, "aria-label" = label, role = "img", stars)
  
  as.character(div_out) %>% 
    gt::html()
}

customer table

from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6104836/splitting-a-continuous-variable-into-equal-sized-groups

use cut_interval() here instead of cut_number() as cut_interval splits in equal width whereas cut_number splits buckets on basis of equal number of elements in each bucket

rating_tbl <- cbind(Y_test, dt_pred_no_prob_test, dt_pred_class_test) %>% 
  rename(y_Actual = y,
         prob = dt_pred_no_prob_test,
         y_Pred = dt_pred_class_test) %>% 
  
  # since "gbm_pred_no_prob_test" is for prob of "no" so subtract this from 1 to get prob of "yes"
  
  mutate(prob = 1- prob,
         customerid = row.names(.),
         rating = cut_interval(prob, n = 5) %>% as.numeric()
         ) %>% 
  select(customerid, everything())

rating_tbl  
rating_tbl %>% 
  mutate(rating = map(rating, rating_stars5)) %>% 
  arrange(customerid) %>% 
    
  # to limit the number of rows in rmarkdown rendered doc
  head(n = 25) %>% 
  
  gt() %>% 
  tab_header(title = gt::md("__BankMarketing Term Plan Customer Response Likelyhood__")) %>% 
  tab_spanner(
    label = gt::html("<small>High Stars = higher chances</small>"),
    columns = vars(customerid, prob, y_Pred)
  ) %>% 
  # fmt_number(columns = vars(prob)) %>% 
  # fmt_number(columns = vars(prob), decimals = 3) %>% 
  
  # table styling to reduce text size
  tab_style(
    style = cell_text(size = px(12)),
    locations = cells_body(
      columns = vars(customerid, prob, y_Pred)
    )
  ) %>% 
  cols_label(
    customerid = gt::md("__CUSTOMER__")
  )

rating_yes_no <- function(y_Pred){
  
  check_cross <- lapply(y_Pred, function(i){
    if(i == "yes"){
      fontawesome::fa("check", fill = "green")
    } else{
      fontawesome::fa("times", fill = "red")  # fa(close, fill = "red") is another option
    }
  })
  label <- sprintf("%s", y_Pred)
  # label <- glue("{rating} out of {max_rating}")
  div_out <- div(title = label, "aria-label" = label, role = "img", check_cross)
  
  as.character(div_out) %>% 
    gt::html()
}
rating_tbl %>% 
  mutate(rating_stars = map(rating, rating_stars5)) %>%
  mutate(Model_Approve_Status = map(y_Pred, rating_yes_no)) %>%
  arrange(customerid) %>% 
    
  # to limit the number of rows in rmarkdown rendered doc
  head(n = 25) %>%

    label = gt::html("<small>High Stars = higher chances</small>"),

library(formattable)
rating_tbl %>% 
  mutate(Model_Approve_Status = ifelse(y_Pred == "no", FALSE, TRUE)) %>% 
  head(n = 25) %>% 
  
  formattable(., list(
    prob = color_tile("white","orange"),
    y_Actual = formatter("span", style = x ~ ifelse(x == "yes", 
    style(color = "green", font.weight = "bold"), NA)),
    
    Model_Approve_Status = formatter("span",
                                     style = x ~ style(color = ifelse(x, "green", "red")),
                                     x ~ icontext(ifelse(x, "ok", "remove"), ifelse(x, "Yes", "No")))
  ))
